Most of the Serializer configuration procedure is carried out by assigning attributes. For example, to decide the names to be given to each of the Spool Files produced, an attribute is used which may be configured to allow it to contain a sequence number if more than one file is produced.

Each Serializer has its own catalog of attributes, which you can create and customize to obtain the desired effect.

The attributes catalog is accessible from the sections where attributes are used, which are:

- Envelopes section

- Files and metadata sections

- Overprint sections

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## **Attributes list**
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

In the attributes list section there are several helper features that make easier to search for attributes, such as:

- A filter based on attribute names. Typing a string will only show the attributes whose name contains that string.

- Ascending / descending sort on each visible field.

- A column that shows whether the attribute is in use or not. Attributes in use are marked with an anchor-shaped icon.

### Data types
The data type of the attributes may be String, Number, or Boolean. Specific properties are available for each type. The attribute type affects the way in which they are used to make up the Serializer configurations. For example, a Boolean attribute is needed to decide whether or not to apply separation of the Shipment into more than one Envelope.

### Attribute properties
![](data:image/png;base64,)

As well as their type, attributes have the following properties.

**Name**

**Type**

**Description**

**Code**

All

Unique identifier of the attribute within the Serializer.

**Description**

All

You may assign a description to the attribute for rapid indication of its main functions.

**Alignment**

String

Indicates whether blank spaces are to be placed on the right or left of the value assigned to the attribute, if the number of characters in the value is less than the length of the attribute.

**Length**

String

Maximum length of the attribute. Characters in excess of the value assigned will be cut off.

**Upper case/ Lower case**

String

You may indicate how upper case and lower case letters are to be managed in the value assigned to the Attribute.

**Decimal places**

String

You may decide how many decimal figures to use if a Numerical value is converted into a String.

**Group separator**

String

This parameter indicates whether a group separator is to be used if a Numerical value is converted into a String. The actual separator character is set by means of the Target Localization.

**Zero padding**

String

You may decide whether to fill in the missing figures with less significant zeros if a Numerical value is converted into a String.

**Approximation**

String

You may decide whether to approximate to the nearest whole number if a Numerical value is converted into a String.

**Approximation**

Numeric

You may decide whether to approximate to the nearest whole number when a number is assigned as the value of the Attribute.

## **Assigning attributes**
Each Attribute is constructed by means of an Assignment Tree. The Assignment Tree has just one root and may have a large number of leaves. Each output from the Assignment Tree is a possible value for the attribute. The Assignment Tree consists of several different nodes, each of which has a type which sets the processing actions performed.

The types of Node are listed in the following table:

Icon

Type

Description

![](data:image/png;base64,)

 

**Multiple selection**

Used for a multiple selection. Each multiple selection requires an attribute for logical reasoning and can have several outputs.

Each output becomes true if the value of the attribute is the same as the comparison value provided for the output.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Single selection**

Used for a single selection with a complex condition. Each single selection applies logical conditions which must have an output of true or false.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Expression**

Leaf node. An expression assigns a value to an attribute depending on the performance of an expression (e.g. concatenation, addition, etc.). The expressions allowed depend on the type of attribute.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Constant**

Leaf node. A constant assigns a fixed value to an attribute. The limitations on the value which can be entered depend on the type of attribute.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Reference**

Leaf node. A reference assigns the value to an attribute depending on the value of another attribute. This node can be used if two attributes are required to have the same value without knowing what value, or if a String type attribute containing an originally numeric value is required. The reference is capable of converting the type into String.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Attachment**

Leaf node. A boolean value that is automatically set by the Campaign Management attachment management. Used to bind the logic of Campaign Management to Output Management. When Campaign Management is not enabled, its value is "false".

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## **Allowed attributes**
![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Attribute categories
There are three categories of attributes.

**Category**

**Description**

**User Attributes**

Collection of customized attributes you can create and set up using the functions of the Output view.

**System attributes**

Collection of attributes supplied by the system which you can use to extract information about the elements being manipulated (e.g. page counters, page numbers, etc.).

**Data Schema Attributes**

Attributes that can be used amongst those made available by the Data Schema. Not all data schema attributes can be used; the user application only shows the ones available.

### Finding attributes
The list of allowed attributes allows the contents to be filtered in various ways to simplify the search.

- Enter a value in the search box to filter the attributes, showing only the ones which have a code or description which contains the value entered.

- Select **User**, **System **or **Data Schema **to switch between lists.

- Select or deselect **Show instance attributes **to show or hide the Fields which the system creates automatically for Lots and Indexes.

### Exporting the attributes list
- Click the **CSV **button to copy the list of allowed attributes to the notes.

- Using a suitable text editor or spreadsheet, paste the contents.

### Modifying the Assignment Tree of an attribute
An attribute's assignment tree can be copied into another attribute. The field of destination will retain all its characteristics but its assignment tree will be replaced by that of the source field.

- Select the attribute into which you wish to copy the Assignment Tree.

- From the list of allowed attributes, select the attribute from which you wish to take the tree.

- Drag the attribute from the list to the Assignment Tree of the destination attribute and release it.

- Click **Copy **to apply the copy.

> Warning

You may only use attributes from the User list as copy sources.
